First and last time trying Rice Valley. I ordered scallion pancakes and there was no dipping sauce. It's always been ginger sauce from other Chinese restaurants. We ordered chicken fingers, which had raw batter on the inside. We also ordered noodles in a "garlic and wine sauce". There was no sauce. When I tried to take the noodles out, it was one box shaped clump. Okay, it's New Years Eve. They are very busy. Things happen. So I called the restaurant and explained my issues. They said they would call me back. When they did, the woman tried to convince me that there is not supposed to be any sauce on the noodles. We did not get any further because instead of offering to fix the order, they tried to make excuses. That is why they are getting this bad review. Also, the food that was made correctly was very bland.

Picture this: It's a Wednesday night and you're craving some fried rice, crab rangoons, beef teriyaki, chicken wings, and a Mai Tai. Anytime you've wanted this you've eventually ended up at Schezuan Gardens at Waverly Oaks. But now that buffet is no more, and you aren't sure where you'll go. Rice Valley might not be a buffet, but you get an incredible amount of food - spending roughly the same as you would at the buffet for fresher, and better food. The Mail Tais there are spot on too. If you're looking for your new Chinese food place now that Schezuan is gone, look no further than Rice Valley. You'll wonder why you weren't going there from the start!

We love to sit at the bar as a couple, but at a table when we come with the kids. The staff are very friendly. Service is amazingly quick.  The restaurant does huge amounts of take-out. This past week we ordered "take out" from Rice Valley. We'd done so in late winter and enjoyed a delicious “take out” meal. Our latest order was Crab Rangoon, Crispy Sesame Chicken, Pork with Black Bean Sauce and Pork Fried Rice. With the exception of the crab rangoon, the rest of the meal was a big, big disappointment. We couldn’t believe the food had come from the same restaurant. The Crispy Sesame Chicken wasn’t crispy, with a gummy coating and meat so tough you needed a steak knife to cut it. The Pork Fried Rice was overcooked and greasy. There was no pork with Black Bean Sauce. Instead there was a very chewy beef with Red and Green Peppers and it was too late to go back to exchange it. This was a most unhappy dining experience. Too bad too for we like Chinese food very much and doubt if we'll try the restaurant again.

I enjoy Rice Valley's take on Chinese food -- the ingredients are fresh and the dishes are lighter than typical Chinese fare.  The restaurant itself is classy and welcoming, although families with children aren't as prevalent as you might expect. Really weird egg rolls. Some minced green stuffing that tasted mostly like celery. No meat, no bean sprouts, no typical egg roll ingredients. It was like a bad hot pocket. We tried dipping them in the duck sauce and then in the mustard, but that didn't help. The soups were just okay. Egg drop soup was like something out of a can. No green onions, no real flavor. Hot&sour soup was fair. Entres were also nothing special. Chicken lo mein was decent. Sichuan broccoli and string beans was supposed to be spicy but was just slathered in brown sauce. No rice included with the entre. The vibe of the place was blah, too. Most of the people there were at the bar to watch a game on their big screen tv. Overall, we were really disappointed with the visit. We won't be going back.
